25|$|Aiming for compromise, Laurier {{advanced}} the Naval Service Bill of 1910 which created the Naval Service of Canada. The navy would initially consist of five cruisers and six destroyers; <b>in</b> <b>times</b> <b>of</b> <b>crisis,</b> {{it could be}} made subordinate to the British Royal Navy. The idea was lauded at the 1911 Imperial Conference in London, but it proved unpopular {{across the political spectrum}} in Canada, especially in Quebec as ex-Liberal Henri Bourassa organized an anti-Laurier force.|$|E
